  Earth's gravity reaches a₀ at 13.1 AU — well inside
  the solar Hill sphere but far beyond the Earth's Hill sphere.
  At this radius, Earth's gravitational soliton transitions
  from Newtonian (g >> a₀) to MOND-like (g ~ a₀) behavior.

    Radius where g_sun = a₀ (AU)           7544.4310624
    In parsec                              0.036573133083

  The Sun's gravity reaches a₀ at 7.54e+3 AU = 0.0366 pc.
  This is about 62.9× the solar Hill sphere.
  Beyond this radius: the Sun's soliton enters the MOND regime.
  Inside: Newtonian ground states (all our planets).
  Outside: the galactic soliton takes over.
  [PASS] Earth a0 radius > Hill sphere
        r_a0 = 1.96e+12 m > R_Hill = 1.5e+9 m

SECTION 11: KEPLER'S LAWS AS SOLITON MODES
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Kepler's third law: T² = (4π²/GM) × a³
  In R₂ language: T² = (64R₂²/GM) × a³
  since 4π² = (8R₂)² = 64R₂².

  Planet            a (m)      T_obs (s)   T_Kepler (s)      Match
  ---------- ------------ -------------- -------------- ----------
  Mercury       5.791e+10      7.5991e+6      7.5998e+6    1.00009
  Venus         1.082e+11      1.9414e+7      1.9409e+7   0.999747
  Earth         1.496e+11      3.1558e+7      3.1555e+7   0.999914
  Mars          2.279e+11      5.9354e+7      5.9332e+7    0.99963
  Jupiter       7.785e+11      3.7434e+8      3.7459e+8    1.00068
  Saturn        1.434e+12      9.2959e+8      9.3647e+8     1.0074

  Kepler's law uses R₂ through 4π² = 64R₂².
  Each planet's orbit is a ground state MODE of the
  Sun-planet two-body soliton. The mode frequencies
  follow the R₂-geometry: T ∝ a^(3/2).

  These are the same R₂ modes that appear in:
    - Speaker Helmholtz resonance: f ∝ √(R₂d²/(lV))
    - Fiber V-number cutoff: V = 8R₂·a·NA/λ
    - Pipe flow: Q = R₂d²v
  The orbital mode spectrum is another R₂ domain.
  [FAIL] Kepler's law matches all 6 planets within 0.1%
        max miss = 0.0074

